{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_6","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'cat .workflow/iphone-app-factory/research-synthesis.md'","aggregated_output":"# WakeTask Research Synthesis\n\nDate: 2026-05-14\n\n## Target user and urgent problem\n- **Target user**: iPhone users (students, shift workers, professionals, ADHD-leaning routine strugglers, heavy sleepers) who regularly snooze, dismiss alarms in sleep inertia, and return to sleep.\n- Urgent problem: default alarm behaviors optimize for sound delivery, not sustained wakefulness; users need a reliable system that ensures they are physically and cognitively awake after alarm dismissal.\n- Market signal: App Store mission-alarm leaders show strong demand, while Reddit users describe active switching due to ad bloat, bypass loopholes, and reliability mistrust.\n\n## Jobs-to-be-done\nPrimary **jobs-to-be-done**:\n1. \"When I am half-asleep, help me wake up in a way I cannot autopilot through.\"\n2. \"After alarm dismissal, keep me awake long enough to avoid relapse sleep.\"\n3. \"Give me strict wake accountability without panic states or creepy tone.\"\n4. \"Work reliably when I travel or change environment (no brittle single-point mission).\"\n5. \"Provide trust-first value without aggressive ads, clutter, or pricing surprises.\"\n\n## Top complaint themes and quoted evidence summaries\n1. Autopilot bypass and relapse sleep\n- Evidence summary: users report they can complete tasks unconsciously and \"have no memory,\" then return to bed.\n- Indicative phrasing from Reddit research: \"my sleepy brain has found a way around it\", \"my problem isn't waking up - it's staying up\".\n\n2. Reliability anxiety and failure intolerance\n- Evidence summary: App Store and Reddit evidence shows users keep backups when alarms crash, background execution fails, or mission completion loops break.\n- High-salience examples: overnight interruption risk and barcode mission edge cases creating panic loops.\n\n3. Monetization and UX trust erosion\n- Evidence summary: repeated complaints about ads, clutter, and subscription shock in wake-critical moments.\n- Indicative phrasing: \"ungodly amount of ads\", \"bloated and too cluttered\", \"just awful pricing\".\n\n4. Tone and privacy discomfort\n- Evidence summary: users react negatively to intimate/creepy notifications and unclear permission purpose.\n- Implication: trust drops quickly when copy tone or permission prompts feel manipulative.\n\n## Competitor strengths and weaknesses\n- **Alarmy (competitor)**\n  - Strengths: strong mission variety, high brand recognition, proven heavy-sleeper positioning.\n  - Weaknesses: ad/pricing frustration, perceived bloat, reliability anxiety in edge cases.\n- **Challenges Alarm Clock (competitor)**\n  - Strengths: clear high-friction challenge USP.\n  - Weaknesses: notification tone quality concerns, limited stay-awake accountability depth.\n- **Instant Wake Up (competitor)**\n  - Strengths: chained mission sequencing valued by heavy sleepers.\n  - Weaknesses: crash/background concerns and brittle barcode flows.\n- **Alarm Clock for Me (competitor)**\n  - Strengths: broad utility feature set and familiarity.\n  - Weaknesses: clutter, ads, sleepy-state interaction risk.\n- **Sleep Cycle / Pillow (adjacent competitors)**\n  - Strengths: polished tracking and insight loops.\n  - Weaknesses: weaker anti-bypass posture for urgent wake-accountability jobs.\n\n## Feature opportunity matrix\n1. Post-dismissal wake assurance\n- User pain: users wake then relapse.\n- Opportunity: mandatory wake-check loop at +3/+7/+12 minutes with escalation.\n- Differentiation: optimize for \"still awake,\" not merely \"alarm dismissed.\"\n\n2. Mission safety rails\n- User pain: panic when mission target fails.\n- Opportunity: pre-validate barcode/QR and provide accountable fallback mission.\n- Differentiation: strictness without trap states.\n\n3. Reliability telemetry as product surface\n- User pain: no trust that alarm stack actually executed as intended.\n- Opportunity: visible morning log (alarm fired time, dismiss time, fallback path used).\n- Differentiation: explicit reliability proof layer.\n\n4. Travel-proof strictness profiles\n- User pain: home-anchored tasks break while traveling.\n- Opportunity: dynamic mission packs by context (home/travel/light sleep debt/high sleep debt).\n- Differentiation: resilient strictness across contexts.\n\n5. Trust-first wake UX and pricing\n- User pain: ad interruptions and pricing surprise during critical wake moments.\n- Opportunity: distraction-minimal wake flow and transparent premium policy.\n- Differentiation: wake-critical trust positioning.\n\n## Differentiation thesis (App Store 4.3 defensibility)\nWakeTask is a focused wake-accountability product, not a clone alarm utility. The core thesis is: **\"reliability-verified, anti-bypass wake completion with post-dismissal accountability.\"**\n\nWhy this is differentiated enough for **App Store** review 4.3 scrutiny:\n- Distinct outcome metric: sustained wakefulness, not alarm playback.\n- Distinct interaction model: two-phase wake flow (dismissal + verification loop).\n- Distinct trust model: reliability telemetry and mission-safe fallback architecture.\n- Distinct product posture: strict but non-creepy coach tone and low-clutter wake UI.\n\n## Design direction\n- **Design** principle: \"3:30am-safe UX\" for sleep inertia.\n- Large tap targets, low-choice alarm screens, clear hierarchy of urgent actions.\n- Visual language: calm high-contrast morning palette; avoid gamified noise during alarm-critical state.\n- Interaction model: progressive friction ladder (light cognitive -> moderate cognitive -> physical validation) rather than one-size hard mode.\n- Voice/tone options: neutral coach, strict coach, minimal prompts.\n\n## MVP scope and non-goals\n### MVP scope\n- Task-gated alarms with chained missions (math/memory/motion/scan).\n- Setup-time mission validation (especially scan assets).\n- Post-dismiss wake-check loop with escalation.\n- Reliability log for each alarm event.\n- Context profiles (weekday/weekend/travel basic presets).\n- Privacy and pricing transparency screens.\n\n### Non-goals (v1)\n- Full sleep-stage analytics platform.\n- Social network/competitive wake communities.\n- Broad wellness content library.\n- Deep wearable biometrics dependency.\n\n## Risks and unknowns\n- **Risk (high)**: iOS background/notification constraints may limit anti-bypass guarantees.\n- **Risk (medium)**: high-friction defaults can increase churn if not calibrated by user type.\n- **Risk (medium)**: strict missions may create household disruption and negative reviews.\n- **Risk (medium)**: camera/permission skepticism can suppress conversion.\n- **Risk (low-medium)**: incumbent brand familiarity may slow acquisition without clear proof-led onboarding.\n\nValidation unknowns for next stage:\n- Best escalation schedule by segment (students vs shift workers).\n- Conversion impact of transparent pricing copy variants.\n- Tolerance thresholds for strictness before uninstall risk spikes.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_8","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'cat .workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec-cross-critique.md'","aggregated_output":"# Spec Cross-Critique (Gemini vs Claude vs Kimi vs DeepSeek)\n\n## Scope and evidence\n- Requested inputs: four independent spec candidates (Gemini, Claude, Kimi, DeepSeek).\n- Files present in workspace do not include those candidate texts.\n- Therefore, candidate-level comparison is partially blocked by missing primary artifacts.\n\n## Blocking finding\n- **REJECT ALL (provisionally)**: none of the four candidate specs are available as auditable artifacts.\n- A spec is not implementation-ready if reviewers cannot quote exact requirement text, acceptance criteria, and constraints.\n\n## Consensus (inferred, not verified against candidate text)\nThe following appears to be intended shared direction based on research + quality bar, but is **not yet validated per candidate**:\n- Product focus: anti-bypass wake accountability, not generic alarm utility.\n- MVP shape: mission-gated dismissal + post-dismiss wake checks + reliability log.\n- Constraints: extend SwiftAIBoilerplatePro, preserve Swift 6 strict concurrency, enforce CI quality gates.\n- Release hardening: Appium/XCUITest exploratory pass + App Store 4.3 differentiation.\n\n## Contradictions (cannot be attributed to specific candidate until texts are provided)\nThese are the contradiction classes the consensus merge must explicitly resolve:\n- Strictness vs safety: \"cannot bypass\" claims conflict with \"never trap user\" safety requirements.\n- Reliability promise vs iOS limits: \"guaranteed wake\" language conflicts with background execution/notification constraints.\n- Friction vs retention: high-friction missions conflict with churn-risk mitigation unless segmented defaults are specified.\n- Privacy posture vs camera-based missions: minimal permissions claims conflict with barcode/camera flows unless alternatives are defined.\n- Offline reliability vs cloud dependency: \"always works\" claims conflict with server-required logic unless local fallback behavior is specified.\n\n## Missing acceptance criteria (hard gaps)\nAny candidate lacking these should be rejected:\n1. Exact mission completion rules per mission type (math/memory/motion/scan), including pass/fail thresholds.\n2. Exact post-dismiss schedule (timestamps, retry counts, escalation behavior, terminal state).\n3. Fallback protocol when mission target is invalid/unavailable (including non-trapping escape path).\n4. Alarm reliability SLO and measurable telemetry fields (fired_at, dismissed_at, wake_check_results, fallback_used).\n5. Permission gating criteria (when camera/notifications are requested, denial behavior, recovery path).\n6. \"Stay awake\" success metric definition and measurement window.\n7. CI pass contract with command-level evidence requirements and artifact file names.\n8. Explicit Appium exploratory completion threshold (minimum controls tapped/screens visited; allowed failure count).\n9. App Store metadata/string audit pass criteria with banned wording list.\n10. Explicit non-goals boundary preventing scope creep into sleep analytics/social features.\n\n## App Store 4.3 risks\nHigh-risk patterns that will look like spam/template apps unless explicitly differentiated:\n- Generic \"mission alarm\" feature list without unique interaction model.\n- Reused boilerplate visuals/copy without WakeTask-specific wake-accountability mechanics.\n- Marketing language claiming novelty without measurable product behavior differences.\n- Near-identical onboarding/feature naming to incumbent alarm apps.\n\nRequired 4.3-defensible statements:\n- Unique two-phase outcome model (dismissal + sustained wake verification).\n- User-visible reliability proof surface (morning log) as core product behavior.\n- Mission safety rails (pre-validation + accountable fallback) as first-class differentiation.\n\n## Boilerplate rebuild risk scan\nReject any candidate that proposes rebuilding these without ADR approval:\n- Auth (`Packages/Auth`)\n- Payments (`Packages/Payments`)\n- AI client stack (`Packages/AI`)\n- Networking (`Packages/Networking`)\n- Storage (`Packages/Storage`)\n- Localization (`Packages/Localization`)\n- Design system (`Packages/DesignSystem`)\n- App composition bootstrap (`CompositionRoot`)\n\nAcceptable work is extension/configuration, not platform rewrite.\n\n## Testability gaps\nCommon non-testable spec patterns to reject:\n- \"Reliable\", \"intuitive\", \"strict\", \"minimal\", \"fast\" with no metric.\n- \"Pass Appium exploratory\" without required numeric thresholds.\n- \"Complete CI\" without explicit scripts/commands and required report artifacts.\n- \"App Store ready\" without concrete metadata/privacy/string audit checklist.\n- \"No secret leakage\" without explicit redaction and logging rules.\n\n## Vague or non-verifiable claim patterns (must be rewritten)\n- Vague: \"WakeTask ensures users are awake.\"\n  - Verifiable rewrite: \"A wake session is successful only if user completes wake checks at +3, +7, +12 minutes; otherwise session is marked relapse-risk and escalation is triggered.\"\n- Vague: \"The app is highly reliable.\"\n  - Verifiable rewrite: \"For each alarm, write telemetry fields `{alarm_scheduled_at, alarm_fired_at, dismiss_at, checks_completed, fallback_used}` and show in morning log.\"\n- Vague: \"UI is simple and non-creepy.\"\n  - Verifiable rewrite: \"No notification copy may include relational/intimate language; copy must pass predefined banned-phrase lint list.\"\n\n## Decision\n- Current cross-critique verdict: **REJECTED (artifact incompleteness + non-verifiable risk).**\n- Unblock condition: persist all four candidate specs to files (one per model), then rerun this critique with direct citations and per-candidate scoring.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_7","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'cat .workflow/iphone-app-factory/opportunity-matrix.json'","aggregated_output":"{\n  \"opportunities\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Post-Dismissal Wake Assurance Loop\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"Reddit users repeatedly report waking but falling back asleep after dismissal.\",\n        \"User phrasing includes 'my problem isn't waking up - it's staying up'.\",\n        \"Competitor set emphasizes dismissal tasks but weak sustained wake verification.\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Users can complete or dismiss alarms while half-asleep and relapse into sleep minutes later.\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Mandatory wake-check sequence at configurable intervals after initial dismissal, with escalating re-alarm if missed.\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"Optimizes for sustained wakefulness outcome rather than alarm-stop event.\",\n      \"risk\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Mission Safety Rails for Scan/Task Failures\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"App Store evidence highlights barcode mission failure panic loops in mission-based apps.\",\n        \"Users ask for mission targets to be validated during setup.\",\n        \"Reliability complaints are high-intensity in wake-critical moments.\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Mission edge cases can trap users in stressful states and destroy trust.\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Pre-sleep validation of mission assets and accountable fallback mission when primary mission is unavailable.\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"Strict wake enforcement without panic traps.\",\n      \"risk\": \"low\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Reliability Telemetry and Pre-Sleep Readiness\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"Users maintain backup alarms due to fear of app failure.\",\n        \"Competitors rarely expose transparent fired/completed/fallback logs.\",\n        \"Research indicates trust collapses quickly after a single missed alarm incident.\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Users cannot verify whether alarm protections are actually ready before sleep.\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Readiness checklist before bed and morning reliability report with event timestamps and fallback status.\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"Makes wake reliability a visible product surface, not hidden implementation detail.\",\n      \"risk\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Travel-Proof Strictness Profiles\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"Reddit users mention deleting/disabling strict apps when routine or location changes.\",\n        \"Fixed home barcode routines break during travel.\",\n        \"Demand exists for hard alarms that remain usable across contexts.\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Strict alarm systems become brittle outside normal home routine.\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Profile-based mission stacks with automatic fallback options for travel scenarios.\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"Maintains accountability while adapting strictness to context.\",\n      \"risk\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Trust-First Wake UX and Monetization\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"Frequent complaints cite ad clutter and subscription shock in incumbent apps.\",\n        \"Users use terms like 'ungodly amount of ads' and 'bloated and too cluttered'.\",\n        \"Wake-critical moments are highly sensitive to accidental taps and distraction.\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Ad-heavy, cluttered wake flows increase stress and reduce confidence.\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Distraction-minimal alarm screens, large controls, and transparent pricing/paywall messaging.\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"Competes on wake-moment trust and clarity instead of feature bloat.\",\n      \"risk\": \"low\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
